<Paragraph>
Formulas are entries in Excel that have an equation that calculates the value to be displayed. A typical formula might contain cells, constants, and even functions. Essential XlsIO has support for reading and writing formulas.
</Paragraph>

<BlockUIContainer>
<TextBlock Style="{DynamicResource HeaderTextStyle}">Features:</TextBlock>
</BlockUIContainer>

<List>
<ListItem><Paragraph>Writing array formulas</Paragraph></ListItem>
<ListItem><Paragraph>Writing Excel built-in formulas</Paragraph></ListItem>
<ListItem><Paragraph>Reading formula strings using XlsIO</Paragraph></ListItem>
<ListItem><Paragraph>Reading evaluated formulas using XlsIO</Paragraph></ListItem>
</List>

<Paragraph>
<Bold>Note:</Bold>You cannot read the XlsIO-created formula without refreshing the formulas. You can use <Bold>XlsIOCalcEngine</Bold> to do this.
</Paragraph>

